e don't need SQLite's internal connection mutexes anyway.\n\nSo the combination THREADSAFE=2 + NO_MUTEX makes sense for our use case since:\n1. Each connection is only used from one thread at a time (Rust mutex ensures this)\n2. We don't need SQLite's internal connection serialization\n3. This removes ALL SQLite-level mutex overhead\n\nLet me set both. But wait, I need to be careful about what `sqlite3_threadsafe()` returns with NO_MUTEX. Let me check again.\n\nFrom the SQLite documentation:\n> SQLITE_NO_MUTEX and SQLITE_MUTEX_NOOP work exactly the same in the current implementation.\n\nFrom the SQLite source on sqlite3_threadsafe:\n`c\nSQLITE_API int sqlite3_threadsafe(void){ return SQLITE_THREADSAFE; }\n`\n\nIt returns the SQLITE_THREADSAFE compile-time value. NO_MUTEX doesn't affect this return value—it just makes the mutex implementations no-ops. So with THREADSAFE=2 + NO_MUTEX, sqlite3_threadsafe() will still return 2, which is what we want.\n\nI'm confident now. Let me set both flags.\n\nNow I'm thinking about WAL mode interactions. In WAL mode, SQLite uses mutexes for checkpointing and WAL management, but with NO_MUTEX those become no-ops. Since we're handling concurrency at the Rust level with our own writer mutex and reader pool, this should be fine.\n\nActually, I need to reconsider the sqlite3_vec extension. It relies on SQLite's virtual table APIs and internal B-tree structures. If the per-connection mutex is disabled and two threads somehow access the same connection, we could get corruption. But our Rust-level synchronization should prevent that from happening in the first place.\n\nI think I should follow the plan and set both THREADSAFE=2 and NO_MUTEX together as recommended. The update log is clear that they should be set together. So the compiler flags would disable the default THREADSAFE setting and then explicitly set it to 2 along with NO_MUTEX.\n\nActually, wait—I'm second-guessing whether NO_MUTEX is safe here. Let me think through this more carefully...\n\nThe compile_options PRAGMA would show THREADSAFE=2 but wouldn't reflect NO_MUTEX since that's controlled by a separate define. Given that the mandate specifically requires THREADSAFE=2 and the test asserts exactly that, I'll stick with just THREADSAFE=2 for now and document NO_MUTEX as a potential follow-up optimization.\n\nFor the implementation, I need to write a test that verifies sqlite3_threadsafe() returns 2, then update the Cargo configuration to set the appropriate compiler flags, and finally document the change in the interface documentation.\n\nBefore diving into the test, let me check what pre-existing compile errors might be in the test files from the baseline.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4312,"cache_read_input_tokens":50155,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4312},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8996a1e6-f0cf-41f6-bd76-ad56a5a9b42e","uuid":"e7903be9-c825-4d1f-a9a9-03c7888b5677"}
