jection cursor lookup, vec0_match, canonical_lookup, and fts_match—which confirms the estimate.\n\nBut there's a discrepancy with the mandate, which lists vec0_match, canonical_lookup, soft_fallback_probe, and fts_match without including the projection cursor lookup. The soft_fallback_probe only runs when there are no vector results, so it wouldn't execute in this fixture at all.\n\nI think the mandate was written from a code review perspective identifying all possible prepare calls, whereas the actual fixture measurement shows a different set. Either way, the directive is clear: convert those four named statements to use prepare_cached, and I should also handle the projection cursor as a fifth one.\n\nWait, let me reread the mandate more carefully. It specifies exactly those four statements, so I should stick to just those and not expand scope. The real question is whether prepare_cached even works on Transaction objects in rusqlite, since the long-lived connection is borrowed at the top of the search function but the prepare calls happen within a transaction context.\n\nLooking at rusqlite's design, Transaction derefs to Connection so technically you can call prepare_cached on it, but there's a lifetime conflict—the cached statement borrows from the connection immutably while the transaction holds a mutable borrow, so they can't coexist. This is the core problem I need to figure out.\n\nActually, wait—I'm checking the actual rusqlite source and Transaction uses a shared borrow of Connection with interior mutability, not a mutable borrow. That means prepare_cached should work through deref and return a CachedStatement tied to the connection's lifetime. Let me verify if Transaction actually exposes this method directly. qlite 0.31 docs.\n\nActually, let me just look at the code and check whether `prepare_cached` can be called on a `Transaction`. In rusqlite, `Transaction` has:\n- `prepare(&self, sql: &str) -> Result<Statement<'*>>`- creates a new prepared statement,