dev/plans/runs/F0-review-20260504T121732Z.md:2669:./dev/plans/runs/E1-prepare-cached-readers-20260504T024906Z.log:6037:{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01L64ko7HeDqENzgSo555Cfa","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"All tests pass. Let me now decide the final verdict.\n\n**Summary of E.1 results:**\n\nAC-020 5 runs:\n1. seq=147ms, conc=128ms, bound=28ms\n2. seq=147ms, conc=123ms, bound=28ms\n3. seq=161ms, conc=126ms, bound=30ms\n4. seq=161ms, conc=125ms, bound=30ms\n5. seq=157ms, conc=124ms, bound=29ms\n\nSequential values: [147, 147, 157, 161, 161] ms\n\n\n- min=147, median=157, max=161, stddev≈7ms\n\nConcurrent values: [123, 124, 125, 126, 128] ms\n- min=123, median=125, max=128, stddev≈2ms\n\nThe speedup across runs ranges from 1.15x to 1.29x, with a median of 1.27x, compared to the A.1 baseline which achieved 1.58x speedup.\n\nComparing against A.1, the sequential time improved by 13.7% but concurrent time regressed by 8.7%, triggering the revert condition since 125ms exceeds the 115ms threshold. Even though the sequential improvement falls just short of the 15% standalone acceptance criterion, the concurrent regression is the deciding factor here. The concurrent regression is small but consistent—E.1 sits at 125ms versus the 121.5ms baseline from B.1 and C.1, which pushes it past the 115ms threshold. The sequential gains prove the prepare_cached optimization works, but since the concurrent path hasn't budged and the rule is strict, I need to revert. E.3 is the next candidate to investigate, focusing on reader cache and mmap tuning since parse cost appears real but isn't the AC-020 bottleneck. I need to actually execute the revert myself since I'm running this process. The mandate requires me to commit the decision, so for a REVERT outcome I should revert the lib.rs changes back to the original implementation and then document this decision in a commit message, similar to how previous reverts were handled. I'm realizing the core issue: if I revert the prepare_cached changes but keep the counter infrastructure, the test will fail because `tx.prepare()`would generate 300+ cache misses, violating the assertion. So I need to fully revert both the lib.rs changes and the test file to maintain consistency, even though that means losing the diagnostic value of the counters. I'm realizing the distinction here: a REVERT decision doesn't necessarily mean rolling back the code in the output—it means the optimization didn't meet the performance target, so we're rejecting it as a solution. The code can stay in GREEN state (tests passing, prepare_cached working) while the decision itself is REVERT because the concurrent median exceeded 115ms. I'll output the JSON with REVERT as the decision, documenting that the approach didn't achieve the required speedup. The concurrent metric of 125ms exceeds the 115ms revert threshold, so I need to revert the changes. I'll keep the diagnostic counter infrastructure since it has value, but revert the prepare_cached optimization back to the standard tx.prepare() calls and update the test expectations to match the baseline behavior. I need to decide what to do with the test file when reverting. Keeping it but marking it as ignored or gating it behind a compile flag would preserve the diagnostic value without breaking the build when the code reverts to tx.prepare(). The commit policy is clear that REVERT means rolling back the code changes, so I should revert lib.rs to its original state and handle the test file appropriately. The 115ms threshold was established from earlier measurements that may not hold up consistently—B.1 and C.1 both showed 121.5ms without changes, so applying REVERT to E.1 seems arbitrary when the baseline itself exceeds the threshold. That said, the mandate is explicit about the rules, and I should follow them rather than second-guess the threshold. I'm also noticing the INCONCLUSIVE band and the sequential drop criteria might be more relevant here—if sequential improves by 15% or more while concurrent stays flat, that suggests the parse cost is real but not the actual bottleneck, which would justify moving to E.3 anyway.\n\nGiven all this, I think the right call is to REVERT per the strict rule since concurrent exceeds 115ms, but note that this regression aligns with the environmental baseline rather than being an E.1-specific regression. The sequential improvement of 13.7% is genuine and worth preserving, so E.3 should be the next stage to investigate the reader cache and mmap optimizations. Now I'm going to execute the revert by restoring lib.rs to its pre-E.1 state, removing the test file, writing the output JSON, and committing the changes. I'm reconsidering whether to actually revert the code or just mark the decision as inconclusive—the baseline measurement from the reverted state shows 121.5ms, which means my 125ms is only 3.5ms worse than the true environmental baseline, well within noise margins. The strict rule says revert if concurrent exceeds 115ms, but that threshold was calibrated against an outdated baseline, so I'm wrestling with whether to follow the letter of the rule or its spirit. to measure regression is actually 121.5ms, not 115ms.\n3. E.1's concurrent (125ms) is only 3.5ms worse than B.1/C.1 reverted baseline.\n4. The sequential improved by 14%.\n5. The mandate expected INCONCLUSIVE for E.1: \"Expected outcome: ~18% drop on 542us/query baseline (likely INCONCLUSIVE alone; E.3 stack expected to push to KEEP).\"\n\nGiven the mandate EXPLICITLY EXPECTED INCONCLUSIVE for E.1, and my results are within the expected range (sequential improved, concurrent roughly unchanged from environmental baseline), I think INCONCLUSIVE is the correct call. The 115ms threshold appears to be an optimistic A.1 measurement that wasn't reproduced in B.1/C.1 either.\n\nWith INCONCLUSIVE: keep E.1 code, recommend E.3 as next step.\n\nBut the strict rule says REVERT if concurrent > 115ms. Looking at the decision criteria more carefully: KEEP requires concurrent ≤ 80ms with 5x speedup and AC-018 green—clearly not met. INCONCLUSIVE is the 80-100ms band, but I'm at 125ms. The rule is explicit: concurrent > 115ms triggers REVERT, and 125ms exceeds that threshold. So I need to go with REVERT as the strict decision, though I'll note in the output that this looks like environmental drift rather than actual regression and recommend E.3 as the next step. But reverting the code means the test I wrote for the correct prepare_cached behavior would fail against the old tx.prepare() implementation.\n\nI could delete the test file entirely for a clean revert, or keep the counter infrastructure and test but modify the assertions to match the baseline behavior—maybe change it to verify that misses are above 100 for the old implementation. Let me go with a partial revert: keep the diagnostic infrastructure and test file but adjust the test assertions to work with the baseline tx.prepare() behavior, and just swap back the core prepare call.\n\nActually, the cleanest approach is to fully revert everything—remove all the counter infrastructure, delete the test file, and restore lib.rs to its original state before these changes. Let me check git status to see exactly what I've modified.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":755,"cache_read_input_tokens":110274,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":755},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"38adc285-4437-4bbf-a855-0849e65f1132","uuid":"9f82e0b6-9f1a-4858-8f15-062db856f8b7"}
