dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:5:FathomDB is a specialized, embedded, high-performing database built to be the memory store for personal agents. Its product thesis is that a single local SQLite-backed engine can serve agent memory end-to-end — store long multi-session histories, retrieve the right evidence, and feed a reader to a correct answer — at parity with dedicated agent-memory systems while remaining embeddable and fast. This report adjudicates that thesis across seven cleaned capabilities: (1) **Agentic long-term memory** (end-to-end competitive parity vs Mem0/Zep under an identical-answerer protocol); (2) **Information-retrieval relevance** (first-stage retrieval & ranking vs a strong BM25 baseline); (3) **Exploratory retrieval** (graph-augmented & index-key-enrichment lift on cross-session discovery); (4) **Deep / multi-hop retrieval & reasoning** (graph bridging on explicit 2/3/4-hop QA); (5) **Answer synthesis** (end-to-end generative QA and the reader bottleneck); (6) **Retrieval fidelity & embedding integrity** (ANN/quantization recall vs exact, and embed-completeness — system health, not relevance); and (7) **Engine performance** (read/scan latency & concurrency — the "high-performing embedded database" claim).
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:9:**1. Agentic long-term memory.** As a drop-in personal-agent memory store, does FathomDB recall and answer over long, multi-session histories at least as well as naive-RAG and Mem0/Zep, under a strictly identical-answerer protocol (one answerer, one prompt, one context budget — so any gap is retrieval, not prompt divergence)?
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:10:- *Measures:* strict full-gold-set Recall@K (all `gold_doc_ids` in top-K); identical-answerer answer accuracy (normalized substring `_match`, abstention-scored); per-class deltas `fathomdb_minus_{mem0,naive_rag}`; abstention_rate.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:13:- *Measures:* pooled & per-class Recall@5/10/20 (abstention-excluded); MRR; nDCG@10; recall delta vs BM25 / prior slice against a paired MDE.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:18:**4. Deep / multi-hop retrieval & reasoning.** Can a lexically-seeded Personalized-PageRank graph-fusion arm genuinely bridge across documents on explicit 2/3/4-hop QA (MuSiQue-Answerable) and lift ≥3-hop answer accuracy above the strongest fused-RRF baseline?
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:22:- *Measures:* judged answer accuracy (LLM judge) and normalized-substring accuracy, per-class + overall; answer F1; reader-swap delta on identical retrieval; n_answered / abstention rate.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:24:**6. Retrieval fidelity & embedding integrity.** System health of the vector stack (distinct from IR relevance): how faithfully 1-bit sign-quantized ANN + f32 rerank reproduces the exact-f32 top-K (recall-floor gated), and whether a dense-embed DB is complete before fused retrieval is trusted.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:25:- *Measures:* ANN recall@10 vs exact-f32 GT with one-sided 95% CI floor (0.90); per-kind embed coverage = n_docs_embedded / n_docs (vectors JOINed to live nodes); six boolean completeness checks.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:34:**R2 identical-answerer parity eval (Slice 25), `r2_parity_eval.py` — pinned COR-2 corpus (`fe973fcd…`), k=10, retrieval-only (answerer unavailable).**
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:36:| Arm | factoid Recall@10 | exploratory Recall@10 | answer accuracy |
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:42:**R2 memory-class go/no-go (Slice 25) — same frozen corpus.** The four memory classes that define the capability (temporal, multi_hop, knowledge_update, multi_session) had **N=0 gold**, so every memory-class delta was null → **DATA-LIMITED, HITL escalation**.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:44:*Most successful approach to date:* none has won. On the only measurable axis (factoid retrieval recall) FathomDB-FTS and naive-RAG are statistically tied (0.8999 vs 0.8982, Δ +0.0017, inside any plausible MDE); exploratory marginally favors naive-RAG (0.327 vs 0.3561). The differentiating axes — identical-answerer accuracy and the memory-specific classes vs Mem0/Zep — remain unmeasured (answerer LLM unavailable, Mem0-OSS backend blocked). The headline parity number **does not yet exist**; the durable deliverable is the shared adapter/metric harness. (See Appendix → Agentic long-term memory for why accuracy is *null* not *low*, and the N=0-gold caveat.)
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:46:*Next work:* [planned] supply an answerer LLM (`R2_RUN=1` + `R2_ANSWERER_*`) and a working local Mem0 backend for the primary accuracy deltas (R2 metric/threshold remain a HITL eval gate); [planned] the R2 harness is reused by 0.8.2 M1 and 0.8.3 D1/D2, so progress currently routes through those studies; [suggested] re-pin/rebuild the gold corpus so the four memory classes carry non-zero gold, else the competitive claim stays unfalsifiable.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:50:**Exp 1 — Base-retrieval recall@K, dense/fused vs BM25 (LongMemEval, n=160, paired, seed 20260614, LLM-free).**
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:58:Fused ties BM25 on recall (R@10 delta −0.019, inside MDE) but does not beat it; fused does beat FTS-only (+0.044, the real dense contribution). Ranking quality (MRR/nDCG) still trails BM25.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:60:**Exp 2 — End-to-end answer accuracy, same n=160 (gemini-3.1-pro answerer).**
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:68:The answer delta (fused−BM25 = −0.019) is numerically identical to the recall delta — retrieval passes straight through the reader, validating LLM-free recall@K as the cheap proxy.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:96:*Most successful approach to date:* the **strong lexical baseline (naive BM25)** is still the bar — nothing in FathomDB's stack has beaten it on the LLM-free recall endpoint. Among FathomDB's own levers, **fused-RRF (dense + FTS5)** is best: ties BM25 (R@10 −0.019, within MDE) and clearly beats FTS-only (+0.044). (See Appendix → IR relevance for the "tie not loss" power call and the fused-path measurement-validity caveats.)
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:98:*Next work:* [planned] 0.8.3 D1 — promote passage-dense to a registered comparison vs fused-RRF, fix the CandleBge Mean→CLS pooling bug, add deterministic vector PRF (D1b); [suggested] dense-only ablation and RRF/text-weight tuning (needs an engine knob + production node-vector-kind binding); [suggested] expose/lower FTS5's fixed `b` (custom-ranking engine work) if recall work resumes.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:102:**Exp 1 — Graph-arm BFS recall sweep, ON vs OFF same-engine A/B (LongMemEval, n=40; 1,907 sessions, 28,883 entities / 38,021 edges, Qwen3.6-27B extraction, $0).**
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:139:Lower b monotonically lifts recall for both plain and enriched, and enrichment is additive at every b — confirming the length-norm mechanism behind Exp 1 and 2. The best enriched config (0.775) still trails FathomDB-FTS5 (0.800, fixed/un-exposed b).
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:170:*Most successful approach to date:* **passage_dense** (BGE bi-encoder, CLS-pooled) — single strongest arm on ≥3-hop F1 and EM, beating fused-RRF by ~0.036 F1. Nuance: dense *retrieves* bridges most often but *composes* context worst (F1|all-bridges 0.464 vs fused 0.552), so its lead is real but its composition is a known weakness. (See Appendix → Deep/multi-hop for the pre-registration, the load-bearing effect-size-vs-power read, run integrity, and cross-reader robustness.)
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:176:**Exp 1 — Base-retrieval end-to-end answer accuracy (LongMemEval, n=160, gemini-3.1-pro answerer, gemini-3.5-flash judge).**
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:184:The end-to-end fused−BM25 delta is **−0.019**, numerically identical to the recall@10 fused−BM25 delta (−0.019, from 0.606 vs 0.625). Answer accuracy mirrors recall exactly — the reader is a faithful pass-through; no arm that fails on recall is rescued downstream.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:193:Swapping nano → gemini-3.1-pro lifted FTS accuracy 0.069 → 0.350 (+0.281; BM25 0.081 → 0.406, +0.325) — ~5×. A weak reader is unusable as a headline (mass abstention); a capable reader is required for usable accuracy.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:195:*Most successful approach to date:* a strong reader (gemini-3.1-pro) over a strong lexical retriever (naive BM25): overall accuracy 0.406, top arm in both experiments. The load-bearing conclusion — retrieval (recall) is the binding constraint and is faithfully transmitted, *provided* the reader is capable; weak readers collapse the pipeline regardless of retrieval quality. (See Appendix → Answer synthesis for why the −0.019 correspondence is load-bearing, the abstention accounting, and the reasoning-model max_tokens trap.)
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:197:*Next work:* [planned] use LLM-free recall@K as the cheap proxy for the rest of 0.8.1 (justified by the 1:1 mapping), re-anchor all gates to gemini-3.1-pro; [planned] downstream graph/dense levers (0.8.2 M1, 0.8.3 D1) target recall directly; [suggested] none beyond — the reader confound is considered resolved (nano is not a valid headline reader).
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:201:**Exp 1 — eu7 real-embedder ANN vector-stage recall fidelity gate (AC-075, Slice 40 / GA), N=7667.**
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:203:| Arm | recall@10 | Note |
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:222:*Next work:* [planned] diagnose the ~4-point 0.7.x→0.8.0 fidelity regression via an engine-version A/B bisect (measurement-only first; re-pointed to 0.8.5); [planned] use verify_embed_db as a resumable post-drain GATE in the fused build path (serve fused recall only at coverage == 1.0); [suggested] close the vector-kind binding gap (no production Python surface registers a node vector kind; fused path relies on the `_configure_vector_kind_for_test` seam).
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:257:The honest headline: on its own internal endpoints FathomDB's first-stage retrieval **ties** a strong BM25 baseline (fused-RRF) and its graph/multi-hop levers are **refuted** on both recall and answer-F1; against external agent-memory and multi-hop systems, the comparison is **not apples-to-apples** because the defining end-to-end numbers (identical-answerer accuracy vs Mem0/Zep) were never measured. Three structural caveats govern every cross-vendor row below: (1) LongMemEval/LOCOMO scores swing 15–30 pts with the reader model (GPT-4o vs mini vs GPT-5-mini) and the judge protocol, so cross-vendor numbers are not directly comparable; (2) several competitor scores (Mem0 2026 94.4/92.5, Mastra 94.87%, TiMem 76.88%) are vendor/aggregator-reported secondary sources, not verified leaderboards; (3) FathomDB's gated 0.90/0.937 figure measures ANN **fidelity**, not IR relevance — it must never be quoted as a relevance comparator.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:259:**Agentic long-term memory (LongMemEval, QA accuracy).**
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:268:| **FathomDB** | **no end-to-end accuracy measured**; factoid Recall@10 0.8999 ≈ naive-RAG 0.8982 | internal | retrieval-only |
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:270:FathomDB **trails on the only basis anyone can compare** because it has no published end-to-end accuracy: the answerer LLM and Mem0-OSS backend were unavailable, and the four memory classes had N=0 gold. The defensible claim is narrow — retrieval-tied with naive-RAG on factoid recall, marginally behind on exploratory. Any "parity with Mem0/Zep" claim is currently unsupported by evidence.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:280:| BM25 RAG | LongMemEval single-session recall | 0.560 |
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:296:Not apples-to-apples (different reader, different MuSiQue cut, different metric basis). The structurally important finding: where HippoRAG-2's KG+PPR **beats** a dense baseline on MuSiQue (+7.1 F1), FathomDB's lexically-seeded PPR **loses** to its own dense/fused arm. FathomDB's graph multi-hop is refuted on both axes (0.8.1 recall, 0.8.2 answer F1); its carried-forward lever is dense, matching the dense-baseline class rather than the graph-SOTA class.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:298:**Answer synthesis (reader bottleneck).** FathomDB has no cross-vendor head-to-head, but its internal finding — a strong reader (gemini-3.1-pro) is ~5× a weak one on identical retrieval — directly corroborates the published reader-sensitivity caveat and the LongMemEval full-context/oracle ceiling (60.2%/82.4%): end-to-end accuracy is reader-bound, so any FathomDB-vs-Mem0/Zep claim is meaningless without fixing the answerer.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:302:**Net.** FathomDB today is a credible, fast embedded retrieval substrate that **ties a strong lexical baseline** on first-stage relevance and transmits retrieval faithfully to a capable reader. It does **not** yet have the end-to-end agent-memory accuracy number that would let it stand against Mem0/Zep, and its graph/multi-hop differentiators are refuted. The carried-forward bet is dense retrieval quality (D1) plus fielded enrichment (D2) — not graph traversal.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:317:**Why accuracy is null, not low.** The primary delta in this capability is *answer accuracy*; with the answerer LLM unavailable, only Evidence Recall@K is comparable. The factoid Δ of +0.0017 is far inside any plausible MDE at this gold count, so "tie," not "win." (Cross-reference: the base-retrieval n=160 study found per-class MDE ~21pp and pooled ~11pp on the analogous LongMemEval classes, and a strong reader scored ~5× a nano reader on identical retrieval — i.e. e2e accuracy here would be reader-bottlenecked, which is precisely why the answerer choice matters before any Mem0/Zep claim.)
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:321:**Harness provenance / known seams.** Harness merged `a1cd7d9`, fix-25-1 `078b882`; codex §9 review was 1×P1 + 4×P2 → PASS. `_build_fathomdb` supports an ELPS two-pass ingest (write doc nodes → drain → `ingest_with_extractor` for the entity/edge graph arm), capped at `_ELPS_MAX_CHARS = 2000` to avoid extractor truncation / IO-timeout. The Slice-25 ELPS golden was signed off as a cross-repo memex artifact. `r2_parity_eval.py` is the shared metric/adapter library (`Hit`, `FathomDBAdapter`, `NaiveRAGAdapter`, `BaseAnswerer/normalize_answer/_match`, `_make_doc_id_of/session_id_of`) imported by `p0a_base_retrieval`, `graph_arm_recall`, and `r6_index_key_enrichment` — so its correctness underwrites every downstream retrieval number.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:323:**Unevaluated / open items.** (a) Mem0-OSS arm never ran (mem0ai backend unavailable, recorded as a clean blocker, arm skipped) — no FathomDB-vs-Mem0 number exists at all. (b) Zep was never instantiated as an arm. (c) The identical-answerer *accuracy* endpoint — the actual headline of this capability — is unmeasured pending an answerer LLM. Any external claim of "parity with Mem0/Zep" is therefore unsupported by current evidence; only "retrieval-tied with naive-RAG on factoid recall (0.8999 vs 0.8982), marginally behind on exploratory (0.327 vs 0.3561)" is defensible.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:327:**Design, power, and the "tie not loss" call (Experiment 1).** Paired design, seed 20260614, 4 classes (factoid/knowledge_update/multi_session/temporal). Pooled MDE ≈ 11pp; per-class MDE ≈ 21pp at n=160. The fused-vs-BM25 R@10 delta of −0.019 is well inside the pooled MDE, so it is reported as a tie, not a loss. The fused-vs-FTS-only +0.044 is the isolated dense contribution. `multi_session` (0.325 fused vs 0.275 BM25) is the *only* class where fused exceeds BM25; on ranking quality fused trails BM25 by MRR −0.088 and nDCG −0.064, i.e. dense recovers recall but not rank position.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:329:**Pass-through claim (Experiment 2).** Two source files (base bm25/fts vs fused), both gemini-3.1-pro answerer, temp 0 / seed 0, identical BaseAnswerer prompt. The load-bearing observation is that the end-to-end answer delta (fused−BM25 = −0.019) equals the recall delta to 3 decimals — no lever that fails on recall is rescued downstream, which licenses LLM-free recall@K as the proxy for the rest of the program. Reader confound is real and separable: on identical retrieval, gpt-5.4-nano scored 0.081/0.069 (abstains ~91%, 27/320 answered) vs gemini-3.1-pro 0.406/0.350 — ~5× — so e2e accuracy is reader-bound; gemini-3.1-pro is the headline anchor. (gemini-3.1-pro is a reasoning model: max_tokens:10 returned content:null; needs generous max_tokens.)
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:333:**Metric-definition math (shared scorer, `eval/p0a_base_retrieval.py` / `r2_parity_eval.py`).** `hit_at_k` returns None on abstention (empty gold), else 1.0/0.0; `multi_session` uses `gold_set.issubset(topk_set)`, all other classes use any-hit `any(g in topk)`; `reciprocal_rank` and `ndcg_at_k` use binary relevance with IDCG over min(|gold|,k); pooled = Σ(recall·n_scored)/Σ(n_scored) skipping None (n_scored-weighted, abstention-excluded). Class-balanced 2-pass subsample, fixed seed, full per-question haystacks never shrunk.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:335:**RRF internals (Experiment 4).** RRF_K = 60.0 constant; unconditional vector⊕FTS5 with a vector-empty soft-fallback before collapse; no `fusion_mode` knob (HITL Option 1A, "documented-only/no-knob"). Determinism pinned by `pr_g9_rrf_fusion.rs` (6 green); filter=None and unfiltered paths proven byte-identical to 0.7.2, so additive features did not perturb the baseline (recall Δ = 0.0000). vec0 TEXT metadata is not NULL-able → empty-string status sentinel.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:339:**Cross-encoder reranker internals + caveat (Experiment 5).** 0.8.1 R1 shipped the `rerank_fused` seam as a STUB (`try_get_loaded()→None`, `score()→0.0`); 0.8.2 E1 implemented a real TinyBERT-L-2 CPU CE (proven to promote the relevant passage in a Rust reorder test) and E2 added a standalone `fathomdb.rerank` API so the comparator reranks the *real* fused pool (codex [P1] fix). Built `--features fathomdb-engine/default-reranker`, footprint-preserving (no network at feature-off / rerank_depth=0). On valid data the CE is null: BAR F1 0.306 tied, M1 n=300 fused_rerank 0.415 < fused 0.450. The M1 F1 figures come from the multi-hop MuSiQue harness (gpt-5.4 reader, ≥3-hop cell), so they index multi-hop answer accuracy, not the LLM-free shallow-hop recall endpoint that defines this capability — included here only because the CE is a ranking-relevance lever.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:341:**Known engine defect affecting shipped dense retrieval.** `CandleBgeEmbedder` defaults to `Pooling::Mean` for CLS-pooled bge-small (`candle_bge.rs:229`), which degrades shipped dense retrieval; the eval harness is unaffected because it uses CLS pooling. The 0.8.3 D1 CLS fix changes stored vectors and therefore must re-clear the eu7 ANN fidelity floor (≥0.90; the large-run value was 0.896 < floor, shipped via a one-sided CI gate) — i.e. fixing dense ranking is coupled to a fidelity-gate re-measurement (ADJ-3). The M1 underpoweredness and graph-arm negatives are out of scope for this capability but are the reason dense, not graph, is the carried-forward lever.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:345:**Statistical confidence / power.** All three experiments are n=40 (10/class). Per-class MDE ≈ 15pp, so any single-class delta (e.g. multi_session 0.30→0.10) is direction-only, not significant in isolation. The load-bearing result that *is* robust is the graph **ON−OFF = 0.00** pooled delta, because it is a same-engine paired A/B with zero corpus/embedder variance: identical docs, identical index, identical kind=doc anti-pollution filter, only the BFS arm toggled. It reproduces both before and after the anti-pollution filter (pre-filter: graph_OFF = graph_ON = 0.60; the filter lifted both arms +0.05 equally to 0.65, leaving ON−OFF unchanged), confirming the IDF/length-norm distortion is upstream in corpus statistics, not fixable by a result-list filter. The prior base-retrieval context was n=160 (pooled MDE ~11pp, per-class ~21pp).
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:347:**Metric-definition math.** `hit_at_k` returns `None` for abstention (empty gold), else 1.0/0.0; `multi_session` uses `gold_set.issubset(topk_set)`, all other classes use `any(g in topk)`. Pooled recall = `Σ(recall·n_scored)/Σ(n_scored)`, skipping `None`. nDCG@10 is binary-relevance with IDCG over `min(|gold|, k)`. doc keys == gold answer_session_ids so hits score directly. All R6 cells had `abstention_total = 0`, `n_scored = 10/class`.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:351:**Why the graph arm is a lower bound, not a wiring failure.** A 50/50 graph-arm probe resolved to real haystack sessions, so the arm is live. The C1 seeding strategy (commit 5da42b0) seeds the BFS frontier from the graph's *own* entity-node FTS (source B), **not** from the query's lexical top-K — exactly the configuration the IR literature says yields ~0 lift. Source-A (edge-fact FTS) seeding is OFF due to two engine bugs: an edge written *with a body* auto-enqueues an `edge_fact` vector projection (`lib.rs:8594`) that throws `SchedulerError` with no embedder configured, and a `StorageError` scale bug appears at ~8–14k edges. So the measured arm runs source-B + traversal only = a recall lower bound. Entity co-mingling hurt (−0.15) is BM25 document-length-normalization bias ("Verboseness Fission"), not result pollution — it persists upstream of the kind=doc filter.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:353:**b-sweep internals.** 8 cells (4 b-values × {plain, enriched}) via `NaiveRAGAdapter`, with fixed-b `fathomdb_fts_only` as the bar. Monotone decrease of recall with increasing b confirms the length-norm mechanism at the parameter level. FTS5's b is not exposed, so the upside cell (enriched + low-b on FTS5's superior tokenizer) is structurally untestable without engine work; the FTS5-vs-rank-bm25 gap at matched b is attributed to tokenizer quality.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:359:**Cross-capability corroboration (not part of this capability's registered endpoints).** The 0.8.2 M1 study re-adjudicated graph traversal fairly on *multi-hop answer accuracy* (MuSiQue, n=300, lexically-seeded Personalized PageRank — strictly dominates raw BFS — fused with BM25, reader gpt-5.4): ppr_fusion ΔF1 = −0.0405 vs the fused-RRF comparator, 95% paired-bootstrap CI [−0.116, +0.031] (n_boot=2000), CI upper bound below the +0.04 materiality threshold → robust NO-GO, reader-invariant across three readers. This corroborates the recall negative here: the graph lever fails on both the recall and answer-accuracy axes.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:361:**Caveats.** (1) All deltas in this capability are n=40 directional except the ON−OFF null. (2) The graph arm is a lower bound (source-A seeding blocked by engine bugs), so a fairer upper-bound graph configuration was never measured at the LongMemEval recall layer — though M1's PPR upper-bound result (which dominates BFS) confirms the conclusion. (3) The single untested optimistic cell (fielded enrichment + tunable low-b on FTS5) is the only reason this capability is "non-win" rather than "refuted" — it requires custom-ranking engine work to evaluate.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:367:**Statistics on the priced verdict.** ΔF1(ppr_fusion − fused) = −0.0405, paired-bootstrap 95% CI [−0.116, +0.031], n_boot=2000, seed 0, on the ≥3-hop cell (n=144). The verdict is load-bearing on the *effect size + CI*, not the mechanical gate: `decide()` returns NO_GO formally via the POWER gate (power_ok=False *by construction* — the ≥3-hop cell n=144 ≪ the 1165 the whole-rule power-sim requires; this is expected/correct for a stage-1 cell). The hop-trend slope (−0.013) is *not* significantly negative; it simply shows no positive dose-response. ΔEM is also negative (ppr 0.3194 vs fused 0.3542). The "pwrfix" power-sim further showed the rule is underpowered even at N=1165 (P(GO)≈0.45 at materiality 0.04) — moot under a robust reject, but a flag for 0.8.3 re-registration (ADJ-1).
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:378:**Why PPR is the strong form of the graph hypothesis.** PPR strictly dominates 0.8.1's raw unseeded BFS arm (which added exactly 0.00 pooled R@10 on LongMemEval and even degraded its own multi_session target 0.30→0.10). So if lexically-seeded PPR cannot beat fused-RRF, raw BFS never would — clean adjudication. Literature corroborates (adversarially verified 3-0): raw BFS ≈ 0 lift over strong lexical is normal (SPRIG: HotpotQA plain RRF 0.851 beats GraphHybrid 0.775 beats BM25 0.742); "graph beats BM25 ~46%" was refuted 0-3 (holds only with LLM-reasoning-guided traversal). Graph multi-hop is now refuted on *both* axes (0.8.1 recall, 0.8.2 answer F1).
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:388:**Why the −0.019 correspondence is load-bearing, not coincidence.** Experiment 1's end-to-end fused−BM25 accuracy delta (−0.019) equals the LLM-free recall@10 delta (R@10: fused 0.606, BM25 0.625, Δ −0.019) to three decimals. This 1:1 mapping is the formal justification for substituting cheap LLM-free recall@K for priced end-to-end runs across 0.8.1 — it demonstrates the reader neither amplifies nor masks retrieval differences on this corpus. Caveat: this is established at one N (160) on one corpus class-mix; it is a strong directional result, not a proven invariant.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:390:**Statistical confidence (both experiments).** N=160, class-balanced (≈40/class). Per-class MDE ≈ 21pp; pooled MDE ≈ 11pp (seed 20260614, paired design). Therefore the −0.019 fused-vs-BM25 deltas (both recall and answer) are *well inside* the MDE — read as "tie/faithful pass-through," not a significant loss. Per-class orderings (e.g. KU fused 0.500 > BM25 0.475 > FTS 0.350; multi_session BM25 0.250 > fused 0.200 > FTS 0.150) are individually within per-class MDE and so are direction-only; their *consistency* across recall and answer axes is the credible signal, not any single cell. Note an ordering instability documented elsewhere: §3 n=160 had BM25 ≥ FTS, while a later R6 n=40 subset had FTS 0.80 > BM25 0.70 — attributed to tokenizer/implementation and subsample, not a real reversal.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:392:**n_answered / abstention accounting.** Experiment 1 arms answered 89–95 of ~160 (the remainder includes legitimate abstain-correct cases and non-answers); accuracy is computed with abstention scored correct iff the gold is a negative/abstention case, and a non-abstaining wrong answer scored 0. Experiment 2's nano reader answered only 27/320 question-arm cells (~91% abstention) — this is *behavioral collapse*, not low accuracy on attempted answers, which is why nano is excluded as a headline reader rather than reported as a marginal arm.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:398:**Scope / what is *not* measured here.** These two experiments measure judged + substring *accuracy*, not answer-F1; answer-F1 is the registered endpoint of the separate multi-hop graph adjudications (0.8.2 M1, MuSiQue), which belong to a different capability and use a different reader (gpt-5.4) and a paired-bootstrap CI / power-gate / materiality-threshold decision rule not applicable to these recall-reader runs. No confident-wrong guard was separately evaluated for these LongMemEval runs. Data artifacts: `0.8.1-p0a-base-e2e-n160-gemini31pro.json`, `0.8.1-p0a-fused-e2e-n160-gemini31pro.json`, and (reader-swap) `p0a_base_n160_gemini31pro.json`.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:403:- Floor constant is **0.90, unchanged** (never lowered). The gate is `tests/support/recall_gate.rs::recall_ci_clears_floor(ci_hi, floor)` — a one-sided test that passes when the 95% CI upper bound >= floor and still fails for a CI lying entirely below floor. At N=7667 the measured point estimate was 0.8960 with CI [0.864, 0.925], so ci_hi = 0.925 >= 0.90 → PASS, point estimate notwithstanding.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:406:- **Vacuous-gate caveat (related, not the same gate):** `ac_013b` ASSERTS 0.90 but does so on the SYNTHETIC `VaryingEmbedder` (~0.73), so it was re-classified report-only; do not cite ac_013b as evidence the 0.90 real-embedder floor holds — it never measured it. The real-embedder fidelity number is eu7. (Several perf/recall ACs — ac_012/013/013b/019/020 — are AGENT_LONG-gated and thus never run in per-push CI.) eu7 perf optimizations (parallel GT re-embed + retained-f32 reuse) were deferred to 0.8.5.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.x-capability-status-report.md:415:- Resumable-gate usage: `_drain_until_embedded` in `p0a_base_retrieval.py` polls drain in `chunk_s` slices, uses coverage as the completion oracle, stops on idle-but-incomplete (stuck) or stall (no progress for `stall_chunks`), and only serves fused recall at coverage == 1.0; resumable across process restarts.
