dev/plans/runs/0.8.0-slice-5-review-20260602T225034Z.md:6:- **Orchestrator independent pre-checks (all green on `main`):** `Eq` dropped from `SearchResult`+`SearchHit`; `SearchHit{id,kind,body,score,branch}` shape correct; `pr_g1_search_hits` (4) + `pr_g1_tokenizer_recall` (1) pass — the migrated-DB recall test is non-vacuous (builds a real v10 corpus, re-opens through the full migration set asserting `before==10 && after==11`, re-measures the same on-disk corpus; recall 1.000→1.000, floor 0.90 held both sides); schema migrations (8) + engine compatibility step-assertions (8) pass; step-11 migration is a NEW drop+recreate carrying the accretion-exemption marker (not an in-place step-5 edit), `SCHEMA_VERSION=11`; Py/TS parity in lockstep (`PySearchHit`/napi `SearchHit` + dataclass/interface + mappers + stubs + exports); X1 harnesses + design memo present. (Stale `results: string[]` exists ONLY in gitignored build artifacts `src/ts/dist/` + `src/ts/index.d.ts` — not tracked, not in the slice diff; committed source is `SearchHit[]`.)
dev/plans/runs/0.8.0-slice-5-review-20260602T225034Z.md:11:`src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:1691-1692`. The step-11 migration drops+recreates `search_index` (empty) and commits `user_version=11` in its own `BEGIN IMMEDIATE…COMMIT` (`fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:348-356`); `reproject_search_index_after_tokenizer_upgrade` runs in a **separate** later transaction, gated on `before < 11 && after >= 11`. If the process crashes (or reproject errors) after step 11 commits but before reproject commits, the next open sees `before==11`, the guard is false, reproject is skipped, and `search_index` stays **empty forever** on that migrated DB → recall silently collapses to ~0. Verified against the actual per-step transaction structure; the codebase already documents this inter-step crash class at `lib.rs:~230`.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.0-slice-5-review-20260602T225034Z.md:15:The P1 is a genuine durability defect in the load-bearing reproject wiring — neither a recall-floor breach (no HALT-to-HITL) nor structural/prompt-induced (no §7 override). Per §9, directed a **fix-1** implementer pass on the existing worktree/branch (`/tmp/fdb-slice-5-20260602T221543Z`, `slice-5-20260602T221543Z`): TDD RED test reconstructing the post-crash artifact (`user_version=11` + empty `search_index` + marker cleared) and asserting recovery on reopen; GREEN makes the reindex crash-retryable + idempotent via a durable completion marker written atomically inside the reindex transaction (gate on `schema>=11 AND marker absent`, not on the boundary crossing). No SCHEMA_VERSION bump, no new migration step (open-path repair logic). Existing `pr_g1_*` tests + recall floor must stay green; re-merge to `main`; then re-review and close.
dev/plans/runs/0.8.0-slice-5-review-fix1-20260602T230351Z.md:15:- New regression test `pr_g1_tokenizer_crash_recovery::ac_fts_tokenizer_reproject_recovers_after_crash` reconstructs the exact crash artifact via a raw `rusqlite::Connection` (v11 + empty `search_index` + cleared marker, asserting `user_version==11` and 0 FTS rows), reopens, and asserts recovery — non-vacuous; was RED on the boundary-gated code ("post-crash reopen recall 0.000").
dev/plans/runs/0.8.0-slice-5-review-fix1-20260602T230351Z.md:16:- Independently re-ran on `main`: `pr_g1_tokenizer_crash_recovery` (1), `pr_g1_tokenizer_recall` (1), `pr_g1_search_hits` (4), `compatibility` (8), schema migrations (8) all pass. Recall floor held BEFORE/AFTER = 1.000/1.000. `mkdocs build --strict` green (X2). Py/TS parity surface intact.
